0–1330":"1270–1330","1300":"1300","1332":"1332","1330":"1330","1383":"1383","1270":"1270","1290":"1290","Eliotstoun, Renfrewshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Renfrewshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Scotland":"Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Sempill","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English, Scottish:  see  Semple  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Semple","meanings":["Scottish (Glasgow): nickname from Middle English, Older Scots, and Old French <i>simple</i> ‘simple, straightforward, humble’ (from Latin <i>simplus</i>). The Scottish name was taken to Ulster in the 17th century, and a Scottish family of this name held the hereditary post of Sheriff of Renfrewshire from the 13th century.","English: variant of   Sample  ."]}]},{"name":"of","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese: Cheng, Jing, Kam Fung, Wai Shing, Wing, Yali, Yuk.","Chinese:","variant Romanization of the surnames 歐 and 區, see   Ou   1 and 2."],"variants":[{"name":"Ou","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Wei, Ying, Ching, Heng, Hong, Jia, Kuang Yu, Li-Ching, Cho, Chong, Chung, Sa.  Southeast Asian Lichun, Ming, Quan, Roeun, Sokhom, Chau, Hai, Leang, Ly, Nhanh, Phan, Pho, Tha.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 歐, meaning ‘to sing someone's praise’ in ancient Chinese: (i) from the placename Dong Ou (東甌), a fief (in present-day Wenzhou in Zhejiang province) which was granted to Yao in 192  BC . It is said that Yao was a descendant of Wujiang (reigned 355–333  BC ), king of the state of Yue (located mainly in present-day Zhejiang and Jiangxi provinces) during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ). (ii) from the placename Ou Yu (歐餘), the name of a fief (located in present-day Zhejiang province) that was granted to Ti, the second son of Wujiang (reigned 355–333  BC ), king of the state of Yue (located mainly in present-day Zhejiang and Jiangxi provinces) during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ).","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 區, originally denoting an ancient vessel for measurement in ancient Chinese: from the personal name of <i>Ou Zhizi</i> (歐治子), an expert sword-maker who lived during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ). Some of his descendants inherited <i>Ou</i> (歐) as their surname, simplifying the Chinese character 歐 to 區."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Sir William I de Sempill of Eliotstoun was born in 1290, in Renfrewshire, Scotland, United Kingdom as the son of Robert Sempill 1st of Largs. He had at least 1 son with Lady William de Sempill."},"et":{"1290–":"1290–Surnud","1290–Male":"1290–Surnud","1300–Female":"1300–Surnud","1332–1383":"1332–1383","1270–1330":"1270–1330","1300":"1300","1332":"1332","1330":"1330","1383":"1383","1270":"1270","1290":"1290","Eliotstoun, Renfrewshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Renfrewshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Scotland":"Scotland"},"fi":{"1290–":"1290–Kuollut","1290–Male":"1290–Kuollut","1300–Female":"1300–Kuollut","1332–1383":"1332–1383","1270–1330":"1270–1330","1300":"1300","1332":"1332","1330":"1330","1383":"1383","1270":"1270","1290":"1290","Eliotstoun, Renfrewshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Renfrewshire, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Scotland":"Scotland"},"fr":{"1290–":"1290–Décédé","1290–Male":"1290–Décédé","1300–Female":"1300–Décédée","1332–1383":"1332–1383","1270–1330":"1270–1330","1300":"1300","1332":"1332","1330":"1330","1383":"1383","1270":"1270","1290":"1290","Eliotstoun, Renfrewshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Renfrewshire, Écosse, Royaume-Uni","Scotland":"Écosse","lifeSummary":"Sir William I de Sempill of Eliotstoun est né en 1290, à Renfrewshire, Écosse, Royaume-Uni, fils de Robert Sempill 1st of Largs. Il a eu au moins 1 fils avec Lady William de Sempill."},"de":{"1290–":"1290–Verstorben","1290–Male":"1290–Verstorben","1300–Female":"1300–Verstorben","1332–1383":"1332–1383","1270–1330":"1270–1330","1300":"1300","1332":"1332","1330":"1330","1383":"1383","1270":"1270","1290":"1290","Eliotstoun, Renfrewshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Renfrewshire, Schottland, United Kingdom","Scotland":"Scotland","lifeSummary":"Sir William I de Sempill of Eliotstoun wurde 1290 in Renfrewshire, Schottland, United Kingdom, als Sohn von Robert Sempill 1st of Largs geboren. Er hatte mit Lady William de Sempill mindestens 1 Sohn."},"ht":{"1290–":"1290–Desede","1290–Male":"1290–Desede","1300–Female":"1300–